                     GENERAL COMMENTS                             5325 1451
                                                                  5325 1451
     Resolved resonance parameters from an analysis of Mughabghab 5325 1451
 (Mu81) were used with a multi-level Breit-Wigner representation  5325 1451
 to represent the total, elastic, and capture data up to an       5325 1451
 incident neutron energy of 1 keV.                                5325 1451
     The evaluation above the resonance region (E > 1 keV) is     5325 1451
 based on a theoretical analysis using the SCAT2 optical model    5325 1451
 code (Be78), the COMNUC (Du70) and GNASH (Yo77, Ar88) Hauser-    5325 1451
 Feshbach statistical theory codes, the DWUCK (Ku70) distorted-   5325 1451
 wave Born approximation code, and the ECIS (Ra72) coupled-       5325 1451
 channel deformed optical model code.                             5325 1451
                                                                  5325 1451
   OPTICAL MODEL POTENTIAL:  The spherical optical model          5325 1451
 potential of Yamamuro (Ya90), which utilizes Walter's (Wa85)     5325 1451
 potential above 20 MeV, was utilized with slight modification    5325 1451
 at low energies, similar to Ya88. For protons, the potential of  5325 1451
 Perey (Pe63) was modified to include an energy-dependent term    5325 1451
 in the surface imaginary potential. The alpha potential used by  5325 1451
 Arthur and Young in Fe calculations (Ar80) was adopted for alpha 5325 1451
 particles. The above potentials were used to supply transmission 5325 1451
 coefficients for neutrons, protons, and alpha particles in the   5325 1451
 Hauser-Feshbach statistical calculations.  Of course, all the    5325 1451
 neutron cross sections depend on the potentials through the      5325 1451
 transmission coefficients.  It was necessary only to adjust the  5325 1451
 the neutron total and capture cross sections to improve agree-   5325 1451
 ment with experimental data. The neutron potential was used to   5325 1451
 obtain all the shape elastic components of the neutron elastic   5325 1451
 scattering angular distributions, as well as the compound elas-  5325 1451
 tic and inelastic scattering angular distribution components.    5325 1451
                                                                  5325 1451
   DIRECT REACTION ANALYSIS:  The coupled-channel calcula-        5325 1451
 tions of Matoba (Ma75) for Te126 were repeated with ECIS in      5325 1451
 order to verify the importance of vibrational states and to con- 5325 1451
 firm the validity of using simple DWBA calculations. The defor-  5325 1451
 mation parameters beta(l=2,J=2+) and beta(l=3,J=3-) from Ma75,   5325 1451
 together with B(E2) and B(E3) values for I-127 in Nuclear Data   5325 1451
 Sheets (Ha82), were used to infer deformation parameters for     5325 1451
 I-127 levels. The E2 strength was distributed among known levels 5325 1451
 in I-127; the E3 strength was distributed among 5 arbitarily     5325 1451
 assumed negative parity levels between Ex=1.3 and 2.1 MeV in     5325 1451
 I-127. The deformation parameters from the above analysis were   5325 1451
 used in DWBA calculations with DWUCK to provide cross section    5325 1451
 and angular distributions for the discrete I127(n,n') reactions  5325 1451
 to relevant levels in I-127. The compound nucleus reaction       5325 1451
 cross section was decreased appropriately for the direct         5325 1451
 reaction components.                                             5325 1451
                                                                  5325 1451
   HAUSER-FESHBACH STATISTICAL CALCULATIONS:  The GNASH code      5325 1451
 (Yo77,Ar88) was used for all Hauser-Feshbach statistical theory  5325 1451
 calculations between 0.001 and 30 MeV. Width fluctuation cor-    5325 1451
 rections were obtained from the COMNUC code (Du70), which        5325 1451
 utilizes the model of Moldauer (Mo76). Preequilibrium correc-    5325 1451
 tions are carried out in GNASH with the exciton model of Kalbach 5325 1451
 (Ka77,Ka85). Discrete level data were obtained from nuclear data 5325 1451
 sheets (Ha82); continuum level densities were represented with   5325 1451
 the Gilbert-Cameron (Gi65) model using the Cook parameters       5325 1451
 (Co67). Particle transmission coefficients were obtained from    5325 1451
 the optical model calculations described above. Transmission     5325 1451
 coefficients for gamma rays were calculated using the Brink-     5325 1451
 Axel model (Br55,Ax62). Normalization of the gamma-ray strength  5325 1451
 function was carried out using the compilation of Mughabghab     5325 1451
 (Mu81).  Calculations were carried out for all reactions that    5325 1451
 produce neutrons, protons, alpha particles, or gamma rays for    5325 1451
 incident neutron energies between 1 keV and 30 MeV. The RECOIL   5325 1451
 code (Ma84) by MacFarlane was used to analyze and unfold the     5325 1451
 GNASH output for representation in ENDF/B MF=6 format. Angular   5325 1451
 distribution systematics by Kalbach (Ka88) were used to describe 5325 1451
 angular distributions for continuum particles, as well as dis-   5325 1451
 crete reactions where direct reaction data were lacking.         5325 1451
